      \field{abstract}{Integration is affected by the curse of dimensionality and quickly becomes intractable as the dimensionality of the problem grows. We propose a randomized algorithm that, with high probability, gives a constant-factor approximation of a general discrete integral defined over an exponentially large set. This algorithm relies on solving only a small number of instances of a discrete combinatorial optimization problem subject to randomly generated parity constraints used as a hash function. As an application, we demonstrate that with a small number of MAP queries we can efficiently approximate the partition function of discrete graphical models, which can in turn be used, for instance, for marginal computation or model selection.}
      \field{annotation}{Overview: In this paper, a randomized algorithm called WISH (Weighted-Integrals-And-Sums-By-Hashing) for approximating discrete integrals in high-dimensional spaces is presented. The algorithm reduces a hard counting problem (complexity significantly harder than NP) into a smaller number of NP-hard optimization problems (MAP inference). These optimization problems are then solved using an augmented version of the toulbar2. Review: This research highlights the effectiveness of reducing P-complete problems into combinatorial optimization instances. Because toulbar2 is a complete solver, the algorithm is capable of reaching an optimal solution given sufficient computational time. Most importantly, WISH provides rigorous approximation guarantees for discrete integration, a task that previously relied almost entirely on heuristic methods.}
